##Structural reflection on the epidemic is a weapon we give to everyone

Vicechina  

Function description, different color vision

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
I don't know if you remember, but in the early days of the epidemic, a 30,000-word tweet briefly sent a ripple through the information stream, amid a barrage of fragmented news and public tweets.

The article is a structural reflection on the epidemic, and its content poses more of a reading challenge than its length. The whole article is largely constructed of academic language, dealing with bureaucracy, ideology, rumor and freedom of speech... different entry points point to the problems exposed by the epidemic. Not surprisingly, the article quickly disappeared, and a number of duplicates appeared.

The Internet was also captivated by the revelation that the solemn essay was written by three post 00s students from the Philosophy Society of Sophia, a youth philosophy society dominated by middle school students.

What do young people think of the epidemic, and what role do they play in the disaster? The answer to this question is as much about the future as it is about the present. We talked to Zehao, one of the authors of this article, about what goes on behind the scenes. The following is a compilation of interviews.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Read More: HTTP: www.newyorker.comonlineblogsnewsdesk2012012012012012012012012012012012012012012

Hey, BIE and others. I am Zehao, currently in my first year of college, my major is still undecided, but I think I will choose Global Cultural Studies and philosophy as my major. School started early this year, and I left the country in early January, so I'm kind of experiencing the epidemic a little further away.

It was around January 18th that I began to notice something was wrong. So I sent my mom a bunch of messages the other day, telling her to stock up on face masks and food, and not to go anywhere for a few days. Because I rarely sent so many things to my mother, so she took it seriously, our family is well-equipped, originally wanted to go back to the original plan has been cancelled. Like many people, my mother didn't realize how serious the situation was until about January 22nd and 23rd.

Since the numbers weren't really scary at first, it didn't feel like much, just an instinctive reminder to the family. Later, when the diagnosis and suspected cases began to climb, I was more worried, and a little anxious at the time because I felt as if there was little I could do. Then I saw that some of my friends had formed a volunteer group called "Go Wuhan | North American Students" . At the most, there were 2,000 students. I joined the group at that time and wanted to be responsible for writing the copywriting. But they had this really nationalistic copywriter, and I wrote, "Yuck, " and I quit. But I had to do something, so here's a roundup of how to donate to Wuhan, posted on the public account of the Sophia Philosophy Society.

In doing so, I also realized how badly the authorities had played a role in the outbreak, and you look at Weibo and think that our country is a kind of anarchic utopia organized by social organizations. For a variety of reasons, I think we need to write a reflection on the current epidemic. Instead of original news reports and critical articles about specific phenomena (such as killing viruses, not people who are sick) , we want to discuss the cause of these phenomena, which is actually a crux-symptom relationship, we hope that more people will understand the former.

I started with a friend, Yanagishita, who was studying in Paris, because she was a political student and could talk about bureaucracy and bureaucracy in detail. Later, feeling that the volume of the article might be too much for the two of us, I found another student in the country who was on good terms with Marxism, Yonezawa, who wrote mainly about ideology. I'm in charge of the rumor section and the whole thing. The discussion took place mainly in the wechat group, since no one slept much anyway and jet lag was not too big a problem.

Zehao asks his friend Yanagishita about writing

Because we read the news and social media every day, we're always getting new bad examples, so we're basically writing and adding to them.

We finished writing the whole piece on February 1, roughly eastern time, and then it was all about the layout and the release.

It wasn't available to the public, and it was so long that I expected it to be around 50,000. It turns out we're alone in the back office with 300,000, which should be more. Feedback, mostly positive, is nice to be (basically) praised on the web, but we don't really want people to pay much attention to us. Since the article itself is of little theoretical value (it is not an academic article either) , we are merely applying the theoretical framework that has been summarized by many predecessors, and some of the new perspectives we've developed to think about this issue are more reactive, so we don't put too much value on our work.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
The article has been posted on 404, but it lives on in screenshots of the big V, though Zehao doesn't like weird

And the reason we're writing this has a lot to do with the privilege we have. I grew up in Haidian District, Beijing, and there are a lot of self-media articles on the Internet about Haidian District, basically describing my life. It's horrible. A bunch of after-school classes, whole neighborhood kids learning from the ground up. And I was not good at math, I really can not learn mathletes, but the school also attach great importance to this, so the promotion of school encountered some difficulties. Since I wanted to go abroad and couldn't take the Gaokao in Beijing because of my Hukou, I applied to the International Department of Experimental High School Attached to Beijing Normal University after a series of interviews and high school entrance exams.

It was in the relatively relaxed study environment of the International Department that I had more opportunities to learn the things I liked, such as spending a lot of time reading books on Philosophy, which the philosophy society took over from the seniors at that time. And one of the things that struck me at the time through reading was that at some stage in human development, philosophy was a discipline that could lay the foundation for Science (!) , and I happened to be not very good at math and physics at the time, so I thought I might as well just learn how to do it. But if I want to take the college entrance examination, I can not have this kind of freedom.

Zehao also did the whole visual identification system for the public ID, but he was more interested in graphic design when he was a freshman

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
So for a long time, I thought I was just a lucky guy in a system. The advantages I enjoyed had nothing to do with anything I had done in my life; it was simply that I had been born into a better family. So I should use this advantage of their own results produced by the community, and even lead us to change. It would be a shame if we, the so-called "elite" , had no sense of social responsibility, enjoyed the best educational resources in the country and even in the world, but only thought about how to make money every day.

That is why the title of our article is not structural criticism of the new crown epidemic, but structural reflection, that's why we spend so much time dealing with possible rebuttals: Because this article is for everyone, in the hope that everyone will read this article and learn something they can do for themselves and protect their rights and interests, it is tantamount to sharing a weapon that everyone can use to criticize.

Actually, I'm quite happy about this, because I wrote an article about rumors and refuting rumors in my senior year of high school. After the outbreak of this epidemic, many people's voices just confirmed my previous theory, you can see that more and more people are starting to reflect. And it's nice to see that people have recently begun to reject the term "throbbing" and "contraband. ".

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Seeing the news -- waiting to be disproved -- reversed seems to have become a new habit of reading during the epidemic

Because of the epidemic, I've been expressing a lot on my friends'network and other platforms lately, but I tend to be more of a silent type in my daily life. Everyday life is basically homework, reading, wechat chat, eating and sleeping. Usually listen to a lot of music, mainly when writing homework when a relief. I usually listen to classical music or movie music, but I listen to the music first, and then I go to the movies. Later, I heard that the "three-body" to film, I also heard the song, corresponding to the plot of the book made a "three-body" film Soundtrack Song List Out. But the film has been pigeon until now, do not know when to release.

When I don't do my homework, I don't talk much either, because I'm afraid to communicate with people I don't know directly, and I don't dare to take a taxi or fly by myself. I don't know how to get out of school without my classmates. Sometimes I would like to see other people go on a trip, but I still feel scared now, but it's OK. I guess I'll be brave in another year. So the chase on station B is one of my usual ways of entertainment, recently watching the A Certain Scientific Railgun and the little round maiden biography. Small Circle inside has a role I always quite like, is called Xiao Mei Yan. I like her character very much, it is extremely brave, resolute, but very gentle. To tell the truth, this girl really miserable, in order to the protagonist small circle, willing to reincarnation of a hundred times, each time two people have to know again. It's hard, but that's the kind of guy I admire.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Puella Magi Madoka Magica

A while back there was a hot topic called political depression, and I can actually understand this situation very well: Because I feel that I can't influence the macro policy decision process, and I feel that the world is too cold, that's why you feel politically depressed (or something like that) .

I have my own sad times, such as when I heard the news of the death of Dr. Li Wenliang, I happened to be in class and almost burst into tears.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Because of the long-term exposure to the epidemic, some people have psychological and even physical problems, that can be attributed to the effects of political depression or alternative trauma

But what I want to say is that we should not allow ourselves to be caught in this situation, because we should realize that the present state of society is not the "natural" and immutable object, but the result of human practice, so we have to get involved in the practice.

This practice doesn't have to BE ROMANTICIZED ALL AT ONCE: I've convinced someone today to start thinking, and I've written an article today, it's also a practice: The key is to realize your own power, to realize that the world can be changed. For example, during the epidemic, I have many friends of my age to become volunteers, to organize voluntary activities, donated hundreds of thousands, one million money and supplies to the epidemic area, I think it is a good way to combat "powerlessness" .

I admit that there is a lot of unfinished business that we should be doing, but that is no reason to despair.

Like when you asked me before if this outbreak had caused me some inner turmoil, I might actually feel that I was stronger. What we express can sometimes be suppressed or distorted, and many people have distanced themselves from me or simply scolded me for my political views, but for me, expressing my thoughts honestly and encouraging people to reflect on their doubts, it's not something I can do or not do. It's my duty to the public as a scholar of the humanities.

After the publication of this long article, the public number and subsequent output of the article, the regular operation of the community will continue. In short, there are many things to do, I hope that we can safely and healthily through this disaster, as soon as possible to find their own "weapons. ".
